<!--
Jenkins Credentials Configuration Template
This file shows the structure of credentials that need to be configured in Jenkins.
You need to configure these manually through Jenkins UI or using Jenkins CLI.

To configure via Jenkins UI:
1. Go to: Manage Jenkins -> Credentials -> System -> Global credentials (unrestricted)
2. Click "Add Credentials"
3. Follow the instructions below for each credential type
-->

<!--
CREDENTIAL 1: SSH Key for EC2
Type: SSH Username with private key
ID: ec2-ssh-key
Username: ec2-user (or ubuntu for Ubuntu instances)
Private Key: Content of your EC2 .pem file

Steps:
1. Select "SSH Username with private key"
2. ID: ec2-ssh-key
3. Description: SSH key for EC2 deployment
4. Username: ec2-user
5. Private Key: Enter directly (paste your .pem file content)
6. Click OK
-->

<!--
CREDENTIAL 2: EC2 Instance IP
Type: Secret text
ID: ec2-instance-ip
Secret: Your EC2 public IP address (e.g., 54.123.45.67)

Steps:
1. Select "Secret text"
2. ID: ec2-instance-ip
3. Description: EC2 Instance IP Address
4. Secret: <your-ec2-public-ip>
5. Click OK
-->

<!--
CREDENTIAL 3: AWS Credentials (Optional - only if Jenkins is not on AWS)
Type: AWS Credentials
ID: aws-credentials
Access Key ID: Your AWS Access Key
Secret Access Key: Your AWS Secret Key

Steps:
1. Select "AWS Credentials"
2. ID: aws-credentials
3. Description: AWS Credentials for EC2
4. Access Key ID: <your-access-key>
5. Secret Access Key: <your-secret-key>
6. Click OK
-->

<!--
Note: If Jenkins is running on an AWS EC2 instance, you can use IAM roles instead:
1. Create an IAM role with EC2 permissions
2. Attach the role to your Jenkins EC2 instance
3. No need to configure AWS credentials in Jenkins
-->

